Gonzales, who is 53, has had asthma since she moved near several oil refineries in Pasadena, Texas, 20 years ago.
EPA data backs up Gonzales’s sense that her family’s breathing problems are “all because of the refineries,” as she told me.
The environmental agency, citing the coronavirus pandemic, announced that it was giving polluters a free pass on the enforcement of pollution rules last week.
The environmental groups’ letter also pointed out the riskiness of moves that could increase dangerous pollution during a global pandemic.
Underlying conditions increase the likelihood of serious consequences and death from infection with the coronavirus.